05114nam a22005895i 9781503619128DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036191287 a10.1515/97815036191282doi  a(DE-B1597)581593  a(OCoLC)1322125306  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0090002bisacsh00aWhat’s Left of Enlightenment? :bA Postmodern Question /ced. by Keith M. Baker, Peter Hanns Reill. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Enlightenment or Postmodernity? -- tThe Enlightenment and the Genealogy of Cultural Conflict in the United States -- tThe Continuity Between the Enlightenment and 'Postmodernism' -- tPart II: Critical Confrontations -- tThe Historicist Enlightenment -- tHeidegger and the Critique of Reason -- t"A Bright Clear Mirror": Cassirer's The Philosophy of the Enlightenment -- tCritique and Government: Michel Foucault and the Question 'What Is Enlightenment?' -- tPart III: A Postmodern Enlightenment? -- tEnlightenment Fears, Fears of Enlightenment -- tDifference: An Enlightenment Concept -- tEnlightenment as Conversation -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has become increasingly clear in recent years that, for all their differences, the many varieties of thinking commonly grouped together under the rubric of “postmodernism” share at least one salient characteristic: they all depend upon a stereotyped account of the Enlightenment. Postmodernity requires a “modernity” to be repudiated and superseded, and the tenets of this modernity have invariably been identified with the so-called Enlightenment Project. This volume aims to explore critically the now conventional opposition between Enlightenment and Postmodernity and question some of the conclusions drawn from it. In so doing, the authors focus on three general areas. Part I, “Enlightenment or Postmodernity?”, reflects on the way in which contemporary discussion characterizes the two movements as radical alternatives. Part II, “Critical Confrontations,” provides a kind of archaeology of this opposition by charting a series of critical engagements by those who have affirmed or demeaned Enlightenment values in the twentieth century. Part III, “A Postmodern Enlightenment?”, complicates the perceived dichotomy between Enlightenment and Postmodernity by pointing to the existence within the Enlightenment of elements frequently seen as characteristic of Postmodernity. The contributors are Lorraine Daston, Dena Goodman, David Hollinger, Lawrence E. Klein, Jonathan Knudsen, Michael Meranze, Richard Rorty, Hans Sluga, and Johnson Kent Wright.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Keith M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDaston, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, Dena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollinger, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Lawrence E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnudsen, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeranze, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReill, Peter Hanns, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRorty, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSluga, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aW